The first virtual service provider is still in Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The Czech mobile market is relatively advanced and our providers provide practically the same services as their Western European partners.
However, there is something missing here - the virtual service provider that forces classic service providers to reduce substantial prices.
Maybe it won't be long.
On Mobile.cz, we have often written that Czech service providers are among the most expensive in Europe.
This has been confirmed by ČTÚ, which has pointed out that the cost of SMS in Czech Republic is more expensive than the other countries of the Union.
Following the last step of the European Commission, roaming fees may thus have a contradictory situation - some of the Czech mobile providers from abroad will be cheaper than domestics.
How can Czech prices be so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lacking the competition that really wants to fight.
This may sound contradictory because we have three mobile networks and our penetration is highly above 100%.
On the contrary, mobile providers are pleased to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
This is often agreed by Pavel Dvořák, the Chairman of the Czech Telecommunication Office, who has previously stated that there is no place for another service provider in Czech Republic.
Perhaps it is true that the classic service provider is no longer likely to have too many chances with its own network (although it is probably hard to find frequency).
But there is another possibility - the virtual service provider.
The step towards the mobile market of virtual service providers has made a significant price reduction, which the classic service providers had to respond to.
In the meantime, even before entering the big fish market, such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile in Great Britain, there were voices similar to ours.
However, it has proven that such providers have a place and can be truly successful.
However, for example, we do not need to go too far.
This February we informed you about the departure of the mobile service provider in Poland.
This service provider was able to acquire more than 100 thousand customers in not only half a year and become the fifth largest service provider there.
In the meantime, the Penta Financial Group is behind Mobilking, which is also owned by U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual providers is the possibility of focusing on a much narrower target group.
For effective operation, the traditional service provider needs much less customers.
It does not have relatively high construction, mobile network operation and maintenance costs.
Virtual providers in the world usually appear as a low cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which are often offset by less service.
For example, Tesco Mobile in Great Britain offers at least 50 percent cheaper SMS than its competitors.
But as the example of the Polish Mobilking shows, it can be a good move to a target group.
This service provider focuses specifically on men.
"The real men choose the Mobilking service provider - who they like to trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobil Entertainment Company operating this virtual service provider.
It is difficult to tell if the idea of a similar to that in Poland can also work with us.
Miroslav Čepický, the spokesman of Vodafone, doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segmental approach based on the majority of virtual providers.
In addition, it is relatively satisfactory for the provision of services."
In Czech Republic, it is impossible to claim mobile providers
