In 1945, the Soviet Germans were asked to join the United States of America.
This is from the letter that is in the collection of the Scientific Library in South Czech Republic.
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, at least we want to live under the US patronate.
According to this desire, some of the Germans in Sudan turned to the President of the United States in 1945.
This also appears from a private archive that is preserved today in the collection of the Scientific Library in South Czech Republic.
In the letter, the Germans of Česky Krumlov ask the President of the United States not to allow the reintroduction of the "šumawa County" to the Czech Republic, which Hitler has already held under the Munich Treaty.
"We have correctly interpreted the situation and really wanted to be sure in the words that the American troops will not come to the German areas as oppressors and enemies, but as a liberator," said in the letter, "Embers who wear Šumava's destiny on their hearts."
As the addition to Czechoslovakia can give hope to the Germans of Sudan, according to the knowledge of the Czech national character, only to brutality, mercifulness, non-understanding, oppression and slavery, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take over the protectorate over Šumava "most and forever".
“We cannot believe that, without regard to the opinion of four million people, this area would be regarded as a foreign country that will suppress and depress the minority, and it would not contribute to the victory of the allies,” he says.
The reason that the authors could not sign, is that the fear of revenge of "Cheh oppressors".
Therefore, if the President of the United States allegedly doubts about the opinion of the Sumawai Germans, it would be enough to hold a referendum in the Šumawa County on whether they want to become part of the United States and live under the patronization of the United States.
Although the text of the letter may seem somewhat naive in addition to the current knowledge of post-war history, some historians say that it correctly describes the expectations of the Sudanian Germans at the time.
