Hepatiit C can also have very serious consequences: if not treated, it can also lead to liver suppression, liver cancer.
Most infected people don’t even know about their disease, because the pathogen destroys the liver cells subtlely, in many cases the first symptoms occur only 20-30 years later.
Thus, early prevention, regular filtering tests are very important.
In three groups, the average of these diseases is much more than that: people who have been transfusions before 1991, drug users and tattooed.
The number of chronic hepatitis C virus infected is currently 200 million in the world.
Since the disease can already be detected by a routine laboratory examination, it is appropriate to contact a doctor when detecting any unidentified symptoms of origin.
In time of detection of the disease can be cured, the virus can be removed from the body, thus eliminating the infectiousness and preventing the development of cancer.
